    <outline text="American structural view of Human Nature" _note="https://www.npr.org/transcripts/1151023362">
      <outline text="Alexander Hamilton and Thomas Hobbes">
        <outline text="Hamilton subscribed to the Hobbesian view: the lives of man were nasty, brutish, and short">
          <outline text="Thomas Hobbes grew up in a very Christian society"/>
          <outline text="English society’s starting premise that humanity was inherently corrupt because of the Fall of Man episode from the Garden of Eden in Genesis 2"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="The Hamiltonian-Hobbesian view corresponded REALLY well to colonialism and authoritarianism"/>
      </outline>
      <outline text="Thomas Jefferson">
        <outline text="Because Jefferson hated God, his starting point was to reject Christian-oriented thinking"/>
        <outline text="He instead was influenced by Jean-Jacque Rousseau">
          <outline text="Rousseau (JJR) argued that humanity’s starting point was a “state of nature”"/>
          <outline text="JJR  also argued that when humanity invented capitalism, property and civilization, that’s when things started going off the rails"/>
          <outline text="TJ wanted there to be as little government as possible so man could be as close to a state of nature as possible"/>
        </outline>
      </outline>
      <outline text="Both men were wrong in different ways, but agreed on a few key ideas, which got us where we are">
        <outline text="Hamilton-Hobbesian view of mankind gave permission for the authoritarian vector"/>
        <outline text="Jefferson-Rousseau view of mankind gave a vector of possibility for progress"/>
        <outline text="However BOTH believed that anything less than a rich, propertied, and/or well-connected white male was property to be ignored">
          <outline text="Women"/>
          <outline text="Children"/>
          <outline text="Other ethnic groups that were shut out of the political process"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="And that’s how we got here"/>
      </outline>
    </outline>
